  <section class="row align-items-center content">
	<aside class="col-sm-12 col-md-6 content-center padding-bottom-xxlarge">
		<picture>
			<img src="https://cdn.ces.tech/ces/media/events-experiences-images/innovation-awards/2020/honoree/hailo-737492-updated-11-11-19-002.jpg?ext=.jpg">
		</picture>
	</aside>  
    <aside class="col-sm-12 col-md-6 offest-lg-1">      
        <h3 class="color-medium-grey">Honoree</h3>
        <p>Embedded Technologies</p>
      <hr>
      <p><font style="background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">Hailo is completely rethinking the traditional pillars of computer architecture by creating AI chips that deliver the performance of a data-center class computer straight to edge devices. For autonomous vehicles, for instance, Hailo&rsquo;s deep learning chip can analyze copious amounts of data used to optimize a vehicle&rsquo;s perception of its environment in real-time &ndash; while significantly reducing energy use. Hailo&rsquo;s innovative chip is also key to fields such as smart cities, where it can help improve public safety by assisting with crucial tasks such as locating missing persons, finding stolen vehicles, enabling real-time traffic monitoring, and improving transportation flow monitoring, cutting down on traffic snarls and pollution. For smart home devices like virtual assistants, Hailo&rsquo;s chip enables devices to process data at the source, translating into more privacy, more reliability, and faster response times. In short, as industries are increasingly powered and even upended by AI, there is a crucial need for an analogous architecture that replaces processors of the past, enabling deep learning to run devices at the edge. Hailo&rsquo;s chip was designed from the ground up to do just that. With Hailo, a new age of chips means a new age of technology.</font></p>
